sentences: Keith Hale (born 6 November 1950) is an English songwriter, composer, record producer, performer and music teacher, most notable for his work with Toyah Willcox, Hawkwind and Ginger Baker.
His distinctive keyboard work and songwriting ability led him to being asked to join Comus in 1973.
Comus recorded an album for Virgin Records in 1974 entitled To Keep from Crying.
Determined to pursue his own musical vision, Hale formed Blood Donor in 1977.
This group battled against a backdrop of punk rock, supported J.J. Burnel, and was signed to Arista Records in 1979.
Blood Donor can be seen performing Rice Harvest in the 1980 ATV documentary Toyah, at Toyah Willcox's Battersea warehouse where they frequently rehearsed.
In 2002, they reunited for a one-off 25th anniversary concert which took place at The Old Market in Hove, Sussex.
In 1980, Hale joined Hawkwind, replacing Tim Blake who left during the Levitation tour.
Known as Ginger Baker's Nutters the band undertook two long European tours and recorded two live albums, Live in Milan 1980 and Ginger Baker in Concert.
In February 1981 her version of Hale's song It's a Mystery reached no 4 in the UK Singles Chart.

He then joined Toyah's band for more touring and TV work including Warrior Rock: Toyah On Tour, a double album recorded at the culmination of a 25-date UK tour, during two nights at the Hammersmith Odeon in July 1982.
Toyah Willcox had this to say in 2011 â€“ "So when it comes down to Warrior Rock, I know it's one of the best live albums ever made!
Hale, along with former Blood Donor colleagues John Bentley and Gordon Coxon released one experimental self-titled 'acid-jazz' album in 1988.
Supported Jools Holland in 1998.
Performed showcase at Ropetackle, Shoreham, 2 May 2008.

Described as 'very much in the Canterbury style of the '70s'.
Whilst in his final year at primary school he won first prize in the Cadbury's National Essay Competition for Schools.
More recently, Hale writes and arranges school music productions, teaches keyboards and participates in songwriting workshops.

He then joined Toyah's band for more touring and TV work including Warrior Rock: Toyah On Tour, a double album recorded at the culmination of a 25-date UK tour, during two nights at the Hammersmith Odeon in July 1982.
In the present day, Hale writes and arranges many children's musical productions in the Kent and London area and teaches keyboards and songwriting at Charles Darwin School.
